    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1905-01-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1905-01-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="748"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d748">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Eddy</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">St. Petersburg</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-01-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 6, 1905</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Replying to telegram fourth, regarding <hi rend="italic">Calchas</hi>, ship
                    itself was liberated as well as 1,712 tons various goods. There were confiscated
                    13,300 sacks of flour, 36 bales of cotton, 472,420 pounds of timber, 77 pieces
                    of electric machinery held over without definite decision. <pb facs="0863"
                        n="743" xml:id="pg_743"/> Against this entire decision appeal was made by
                    the Russian procurer. Have telegraphed to Greener, asking him for information
                    regarding whereabouts liberated cargo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eddy.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
